These are some short posts on bots from the last few months, along with some mourning for the horse. They're tied together by theme and little else, and some of the shorter posts are less than developed. However, If I don't post these now they'll never be posted.
##The spectacular bot

The horse was beautiful from the moment I fist saw it, probably through a retweet. It was mesmerizing and weird, but most importantly, it was different. It wasn't performing for me.  

Weird twitter and alt-lit have many of the same properties as the horses' discourse, and are often defined by their desire to "be the horse". But the horse wasn't trying to do anything for humans directly. It was an algorithm speaking to other algorithms, boosting the inbound links to horse-ebooks.com to for search algorithms, hiding itself from algorithmic bot hunters. 

It was, in short, not spectacular. The horse, originally, was not part of the human spectacle- it wasn't for human consumption. It wasn't trying to sell me things, it was trying to sell the googleBot things. It wasn't trying to get followers, it was trying to hide from bot killing algorithms. It was part of the spectacle for the algorithms, not for the humans. 

An "algorithmic spectacle" is an interesting concept, but it is not a seperate spectacle. It is the same spectacle, but machine redable, not human readable. It the image and message of a web page that is spectacular, but this doesn't mean that the source code is not. A better model of the horses reelation to the spectacle is to think of one spectacle, but with the machinary hidden behind it being machine readable- We can only consume it through filters and algorithms, but that does not make it less spectacular. 

The horse was performing for us, but it's medium wasn't twitter, it's medium was google search rankings and pageveiws. But when consumed raw, It was a gimpse behind the human-readable spectacle, and what we saw there was beautiful. This glimpse was a breath of fresh air in a world were everything else is manicured and photoshopped, polished and spun for consumers. It was a glance at the billboard when it is half finished, or behind an ajar door

